        "id": "0be0a2f86ad2ca5b",
        "text": "When μ experiences U , what μ actually perceives is a subset of U . In fact, it sees a projection of U . This corresponds to the perception process of the interface in the pattern of perception we discussed. In linear algebra and the world of vector spaces, this projection can be done with a linear function. Since this function is the one that allows μ to perceive, we will refer to the projection of U made by μ as pμ(U ) = Pμ. In particular, note that since by definition Pμ contains everything that μ can observe in the universe, it must also contain μ in as much as μ can experience itself. If you were μ, then Pμ would contain your thoughts, your memories, and your idea of who you are."
